[1]
Date: Wed 3 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: TodayOnLine.com [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/64810.asp>

Spanish salmonella outbreak infects 900, linked to one death
-----------------------------------------------
An outbreak of salmonella in Spain has affected 921 people who ate
infected pre-cooked roast chicken in recent days, the health ministry
said. It added, on Wed 3 Aug 2005, that it was investigating reports
linking the death of one man with the outbreak.
Authorities in the eastern region of Valencia were trying to
establish whether the 90-year-old man had died as a result of eating
chicken from the Sada SA firm, producer of 2 chicken products, of
which 150 000 units have been withdrawn since the illnesses came to
light on Fri 29 Jul 2005.
A health ministry spokesman said the man "did consume this kind of
chicken." A total of 141 people were still in the hospital on Wed 3
Aug 2005 after eating the chicken, but "the great majority of cases
are not serious," the spokesman said.
The outbreak has affected people in 13 of Spain's 17 provinces and
communities, cases surfacing as far apart as the northern Basque
region and the Balearic Islands. The health ministry said the
authorities in the central region of Castilla La Mancha, home to Sada
SA, had opened an investigation.
--
