[2]
Date: Wed 3 Aug 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EITB24.com [edited]
<http://www.eitb24.com/noticia_en.php?id=80193>

43 might have salmonellosis in the Basque Autonomous Region and
Navarre. 9 out of 21 ate the associated product in the Basque region
of Bizkaia, whereas the remaining 12 ate it abroad. The number of
affected stands at 790.
The number of people affected by salmonellosis in the Basque
Autonomous Region, possibly linked with the consumption of chicken,
stands at 21. The food poisoning could be connected with "Pimpollo"
and "Sada" branded vacuum-packed roast chicken, the health councilor
Gabriel Inclan reported.
9 out of 21 ate the product in the Basque region of Bizkaia, whereas
the remaining 12 ate it abroad. One of those 12 is a 76-year-old man
who is out of danger. He is the only one of the 21 who remains in the
hospital. The rest of the poisoned "progress satisfactorily," sources
said.
This type of salmonella causes "basically diarrhea," Inclan stated,
trying to calm the citizens, saying that, due to the "incubation
period, new cases could come up."
The batch was withdrawn from the market, the Basque government said.
However, "if anyone has "Pimpollo" or "Sada" branded chicken at home,
throw it away," the person in charge of the health department
advised. Likewise, those who develop symptoms of being intoxicated
should be in contact with the regional minister.
